  "issue_title": "First user-PRs GraphQL request 502s every cycle",
  "issue_body": "### Description\n\n`load_miners_prs` issues its first paginated GraphQL request at `first: 100`. GitHub's GraphQL backend has a 10s processing timeout, and as our QUERY fetches REALLY a lot of data, at `first: 100` the query _likely_ exceeds the timeout and surfaces as 502 from GitHub's gateway. \n\nThe retry path inside `get_github_graphql_query` halves to 50, then halves to 25, then 12 ... until succeeds. Sufficient page size depends per miner and some may waste up to 3 cycles here, depending on how heavy are their PRs. Thus said I assume plain lowering constant from 100 -> 50 doesn't solve the problem here and we should maybe consider remembering the last succeed page size per miner.\n\n### Steps to Reproduce\n\n1. Run the validator's scoring cycle against any miner with a non-trivial PR history (legacy/PAT path). Firstly seen in https://github.com/entrius/gittensor/pull/947\n2. Watch validator logs during `*****Fetching PRs*****`.\n3. Observe the first attempt against `/graphql` returns 502.\n\n### Expected Behavior\n\nThe first GraphQL request for each miner succeeds without retry under normal GitHub conditions.\n\n### Actual Behavior\n\n```\n2026-05-07 22:23:39.042 | WARNING  | GraphQL request for PRs failed with status 502 (attempt 1/8), page size set to 50, retrying in 5s...\n```\n\nFires once per miner on the very first page. Every miner pays on every cycle.\n\n### Additional Context\n\nGitHub docs: <https://docs.github.com/en/graphql/overview/rate-limits-and-query-limits-for-the-graphql-api>:\n\n> If GitHub takes more than 10 seconds to process an API request, GitHub will terminate the request and you will receive a timeout response.\n\nRecommended mitigations from the same page include \"use smaller values for `first` or `last` arguments and paginate through results\" and \"avoid requesting deeply nested objects unless necessary\".\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-11T20:39:57Z",
